subsection.p:
Sage uses integers to label vertices, starting the count at 1, instead of letters.  Elements by default are printed using cycle notation which we will see described carefully in Chapter5.    Here is an example, with both the mathematics and Sage.  For the Sage part, we create the group of symmetries and then create the symmetry \rho_2 with coercion, followed by outputting the element in cycle notation.  Then we create just the bottom row of the notation we are using for permutations.  \rho_2=
        \begin{pmatrix}
        A & B & C\\
        C & A & B
        \end{pmatrix}
        =
        \begin{pmatrix}
        1 & 2 & 3\\
        3 & 1 & 2
        \end{pmatrix}
